“Just One of the Guys” was the first single released from Jenny Lewis’s third solo album Voyager album. Beck produced the folky pop song and also sings back up vocals.

The accompanying video stars actresses Anne Hathaway, Kristen Stewart, and Brie Larson and went viral upon release.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Irvcf6dCk-k

annotations:
When I look at myself, all I can see
 I’m just another lady without a baby

No matter how hard she trying not to care, she can’t help but feel that she’s incomplete as a woman in her 30’s without children. Even though she knows she shouldn’t worry about what ladies are “supposed to do,” she has internalized societal expectations for herself.

No matter how hard I try to be just one of the guys
 There’s a little something inside that won’t let me

No matter how hard she tries to grow and continue to fit in with her male friends, and regardless of how much they love and understand her, there are fundamental and bioligical differences that don’t allow her to let her guard down. They don’t have to worry the same way she does. Her uterus, her biological clock, has a desire to start a family.
Locked in this bathroom, full of tears

This is 100% a reference to taking a pregnancy test. Either she wants a baby and can’t have one; or gets pregnant and knows if she wants a baby this is it, even if she’s not ready; or the mixed feelings that come with a miscarriage.

No matter how hard I try to have an open mind
 There’s a little voice inside that prevents me

She used to be able to let loose and let whatever happen happen. This could be sleeping with whoever / dating whoever / doing whatever she felt like. Now there is always something reminding her of this or that. She can’t be free like her friends with a dick because she has a vagina and a uterus, period (no pun intended). She has to think about a worthy partner, and kids (if she wants them, nows the time).

If I get caught being rude in a conversation
 With a child bride on her summer vacation

The singer grows older along with her close friends. She’s never had issues relating to her male friends, but now does. She keeps dating people close to her age or older while her male friends' girlfriends/wives keep getting younger. She has to worry about fertility and kids, while they can just keep worrying about getting good ass. Even a cool, confident woman would eventually find it unfair.

Her friends are dating care-free, younger women. On one hand, she can’t relate to them. On the other hand, there is some disconnect because as a woman of a certain age it’s not acceptable for her to date some young / carefree kid. She has had to grow up and her male friends can still be free to make mistakes.
Cop

Cop, here, is used as a stand-in for the general idea of deterrence. In Philosophy of Law, ‘deterrence factor’ is a major contributing reason behind the validity, preservation and importance of police aka ‘cops.’ Here Jenny is alluding to the potentially suppressive nature of cops, preventing her from thinking freely. In Orwell’s 1984, the Thought Police helped Big Brother to regulate the thinking of the Proletariots, even instituting new words to advance the state’s interest.
But I been the only sister to my own sorrow

This almost seem to be a statement about abstinence. Another name for the Virgin Mary is “Our Lady Of Sorrows”. The Virgin Mary is considered to be a saint of ‘heartbreak’, and here Jenny is the only sister (nun) in her own convent of sorrow.

It is very interesting the parallel between this line and one from Nick Cave And The Bad Seeds' “Do You Love Me”

I’d love her till the day that I died
And I kissed away a thousand tears
My lady of the Various Sorrows
Some begged, some borrowed, some stolen
How I live, it got me here
Years of constant touring have kept Jenny from being in committed relationships or raising a family

No matter how hard I try to have an open mind
 There’s a little clock inside that keeps ticking

The second line here refers to the proverbial maternal clock, used to describe the “natural” female need to procreate.



The speaker says she wants to have an “open mind” in that she wants to think of other ways of being beside being a mother, but her biological clock her prevents her from doing so.
And I have begged for you and I have borrowed

Lewis here interpolates the common phrase “to beg borrow and steal” signifying desperation. The phrase actually originates in Chaucer’s “Man of Law” from The Canterbury Tales.

Maugre thine head thou must for indigence
Or steal, or beg, or borrow thy dispence.

description.plain:
“There is only one moment of digital manipulation on the record: a brief chirrup of auto-tune in the middle of Little White Dove.

“That came about because Beck was altering my demo vocal, to show me how he wanted me to sing the song,” she says.

“But when I heard it I said, ‘That’s got to stay! That’s the coolest thing in the whole song.’

“We had like a long talk about it – that people would think it was a mistake. But this is the stuff that excites me about record making: little happy accidents.


BBC News

annotations: I’m the heroin

In 2017, Jenny Lewis' mother was dying of liver cancer. Lewis would visit her every day and would often write down little phrases that her increasingly heavily medicated mother would say. Some of the phrases were incorporated into this album. About her mother’s condition, Lewis said:

She had liver cancer. From untreated hepatitis C. She was a lifelong heroin addict and also mentally ill and . . . just a really sad situation.

body.plain: “Head Underwater” is the first track on Jenny Lewis' third solo album The Voyager.

annotations: There’s a little bit of sand left in the hourglass

One of the themes of the album Voyager, of which this is the opening track, is what it’s like to be a woman, single and without child, in her 30s. This phrase means there is still time left.



The word choice here is also notable, as an “hourglass figure” represents the idealized, fertile woman.
I been losing sleep

Jenny Lewis has mentioned in numerous interviews that she suffered a serious bout of insomnia while working on this album. She told The New York Times Magazine that part of her regretted having shared:

Now everyone’s asking me about insomnia, which I’m terrified is going to happen to me again,” she said. “You can’t think about it too much, and everyone’s asking me about it, and I’m like, ‘I’m fine, I’m fine.’ But, [expletive], am I not going to get to sleep again?”

annotations: I’m wired on Red Bull and Hennessy

Here, the song’s narrator is wired on a drink mix that is both loaded with caffeine and alcohol.

Because of the caffeine in Red Bull along with Hennessy itself, it’s a heart attack waiting to happen.



Furthermore, it’s bad to mix Red Bull with any alcoholic drink, because caffeine can mask the influence of alcohol and may lead a person to misinterpret their actual level of intoxication.

body.plain: “She’s Not Me” is the second track on Jenny Lewis' third solo album The Voyager.

annotations:
Heard she’s having your baby
 And everything’s so amazing

Her ex is allegedly in a committed relationship with a new woman, expecting a child and moving on with his life. Karma seems to have awarded him with a great life, while she is left to endure the heartache of knowing that losing him is entirely her fault.

But she’s not me
 She’s easy

Jenny knows she is difficult, but yet also knows she’s worth it. She understands her imperfections but also chides her former lover for fleeing to an “easier” yet—presumably—less-rewarding relationship.
